            <section id="long-term" class="mb-12">
                 <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-center text-[#FF6B6B] mb-8">The Long-Term Toll of Regular Consumption</h2>
                <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
                    <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-lg p-6 text-center">
                        <p class="icon-unicode text-[#FF6B6B]">‚öñÔ∏è</p>
                        <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-2 mb-2">Obesity & Weight Gain</h3>
                        <p>Liquid sugar calories are less filling, leading to higher overall calorie intake. Linked strongly to visceral (belly) fat.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-lg p-6 text-center">
                        <p class="icon-unicode text-[#FFD166]">ü©∏</p>
                        <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-2 mb-2">Type 2 Diabetes</h3>
                        <p>Drives insulin resistance. Drinking just one soda per day can increase the risk of type 2 diabetes by over 20%.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-lg p-6 text-center">
                        <p class="icon-unicode text-[#118AB2]">‚ù§Ô∏è</p>
                        <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-2 mb-2">Heart Disease</h3>
                        <p>Contributes to risk factors like high blood pressure, high LDL ("bad") cholesterol, and inflammation.</p>
                    </div>
                     <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-lg p-6 text-center">
                        <p class="icon-unicode text-[#06D6A0]">ü¶¥</p>
                        <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-2 mb-2">Bone Health Issues</h3>
                        <p>High phosphoric acid content can interfere with calcium absorption, potentially leading to lower bone density over time.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-lg p-6 text-center">
                        <p class="icon-unicode" style="color: #6a4c93;"> kidneys </p>
                        <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-2 mb-2">Kidney Disease</h3>
                        <p>High sugar and phosphoric acid levels are taxing on the kidneys. Drinking 2+ colas per day has been linked to a doubled risk of chronic kidney disease.</p>
                    </div>
                     <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-lg p-6 text-center">
                        <p class="icon-unicode text-[#073B4C]">üß†</p>
                        <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-2 mb-2">Increased Dementia Risk</h3>
                        <p>High blood sugar levels are associated with an increased risk of dementia, including Alzheimer's disease.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>

             <section id="other-culprits" class="mb-12">
                <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-center text-[#118AB2] mb-8">Beyond Sugar: Other Ingredients of Note</h2>
                <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
                    <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-lg p-6 md:p-8">
                        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-2 text-center">Caffeine Content</h3>
                        <p class="text-sm text-center mb-4 text-gray-600">While less than coffee, the caffeine in cola is a stimulant that contributes to its effects and potential for dependency.</p>
                        <div class="chart-container h-64">
                            <canvas id="caffeineChart"></canvas>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-lg p-6 md:p-8 text-center flex flex-col justify-center">
                        <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-[#073B4C] mb-2">What About "Diet" or "Zero Sugar"?</h3>
                         <p class="text-base mb-4">These versions replace sugar with artificial sweeteners like aspartame and acesulfame potassium. While they eliminate sugar calories, their long-term health effects are still debated. Some studies link regular consumption of artificial sweeteners to an altered gut microbiome, potential changes in metabolic response, and even an increased craving for sweet foods.</p>
                         <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">The verdict: Likely better than the sugary version, but water is unequivocally the healthier choice.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>
